  "summary": "Hercule Poirot observes that Frank Carter, a former clerk, is now employed as a gardener for Alastair Brent. While walking toward the villa, Poirot overhears a dispute between Miss Monteiro and Brent regarding the rudeness of Brent's American relative, Julia. In the dining room, Brent expresses his unhappiness to Julia and Lady Olivia concerning the tension between the women. When Poirot inquires about the new gardener, Brent explains that the man was hired to replace a previous gardener named Burton. Brent recalls that McAllister recommended the new man, whose name is something like \"Dunning\" or \"Sembler,\" and notes he is paid two pounds and fifteen pence.\n\nDuring breakfast, Jane Olivia engages in a passionate argument with Brent about social change and the status quo. Brent expresses his disdain for radical ideas and his desire for stability, prompting Polly to ask what would happen if he were \"eliminated.\" Later, Brent takes Poirot on a tour of his garden, showing him the rock garden and various flowerbeds.\n\nThe peace is interrupted by a gunshot from the laurel bushes. Howard Leeks emerges from the bushes wrestling with Frank Carter, who is holding a revolver. Leeks claims he caught Carter red-handed after Carter shot at Brent. Carter vehemently denies the accusation, claiming he was merely trimming branches when a gun fell at his feet and he picked it up by reflex; he further accuses Poirot of setting him up. Jane Olivia arrives at the scene, where Howard Lacy informs her that he has just saved her uncle's life.",
